Understanding the blunt and frank nature of his corre- spondent, he affects a similar style, and presents the facts without comment, but with much skill in bringing his best achievements into the foreground, and in mak- ing it appear that the retreat of the Parthians was due to their dread of his prowess. The letter presents a side of Cicero’s life which is brought out nowhere else. It has also many points of resem- blance to Caesar’s Commentaries on the Gallie XVar.
